OL,3,CWhere can you see the Northern Lights
OL,4,Ctonight?
OL,6,FCharged particles from the sun,
OL,7,Fprimarily electrons and protons,
OL,8,Fcollide with gases in the Earth's
OL,9,Fatmosphere, typically oxygen and
OL,10,Fnitrogen.
OL,12,FThese collisions emit light at various
OL,13,Fwavelengths, creating vibrant displays
OL,14,Fof colour in the sky, often appearing
OL,15,Fas curtains, arcs, or bands of light.
OL,17,FThe colours are determined by the type
OL,18,Fof gas particles involved and the
OL,19,Faltitude at which the collisions occur.
